1
00:00:44,978 --> 00:00:50,788
- We should have taken the Honda.
- Where would we have put the luggage?

2
00:00:54,166 --> 00:00:55,968
- You're very strong.
- Keep pushing!

3
00:00:57,227 --> 00:01:00,793
This is the last holiday I’m ever going on with you.

4
00:01:00,794 --> 00:01:02,385
Where did you get all those muscles?

5
00:01:04,168 --> 00:01:06,497
More, more, more! Don't quit now.

6
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:08,448
How much further?

7
00:01:08,616 --> 00:01:10,672
It's only a couple of million more miles.

8
00:01:11,406 --> 00:01:12,446
A couple of what?

9
00:01:12,572 --> 00:01:15,276
A couple of million more miles.

10
00:01:15,276 --> 00:01:17,013
Now right up here we're gonna stop.

11
00:01:17,014 --> 00:01:18,253
Keep pushing, don't quit!

12
00:01:18,287 --> 00:01:20,047
Mexico, next time.

13
00:01:20,069 --> 00:01:21,964
- Hawaii is better.
- Yeah.

14
00:01:25,125 --> 00:01:27,134
Hold it, hold it, hold it! That's good.

15
00:01:35,444 --> 00:01:36,779
Now what you gonna do?

16
00:01:36,973 --> 00:01:38,317
I'm gonna try and get us some...

17
00:01:38,317 --> 00:01:39,790
- help.
- help.

18
00:01:45,428 --> 00:01:48,116
- Come on, let's have a snowball fight!
- Oh no! No!

19
00:01:49,455 --> 00:01:49,950
No!

20
00:01:52,140 --> 00:01:54,093
Daddy! Daddy, come on!

21
00:01:54,093 --> 00:01:55,414
Help me, Daddy!

22
00:02:08,836 --> 00:02:11,884
Yes... Do you have the number for emergency road service?

23
00:04:44,812 --> 00:04:45,812
Thank you, Stan.

24
00:04:45,813 --> 00:04:47,470
lf you want a hand with anything,

25
00:04:47,494 --> 00:04:49,126
just give me a shout, Mr. Russell.

26
00:04:49,126 --> 00:04:50,140
I will, thanks.

27
00:05:36,618 --> 00:05:37,608
Mr. Russell?

28
00:05:45,888 --> 00:05:46,408
Daddy!

29
00:05:49,119 --> 00:05:49,639
Catch!

30
00:05:56,418 --> 00:05:57,618
Mr. Russell...

31
00:06:09,129 --> 00:06:12,189
You know that this piece is going to Seattle too, Estancia?

32
00:06:12,610 --> 00:06:13,788
Yes, sir.

33
00:06:15,553 --> 00:06:16,058
Good.

34
00:06:31,152 --> 00:06:33,522
At first, I have to admit I was in shock.

35
00:06:34,196 --> 00:06:36,712
I just functioned automatically. I didn't feel anything.

36
00:06:38,367 --> 00:06:40,354
Then one day it hit me:

37
00:06:41,657 --> 00:06:43,433
Joanna and Kathy are gone.

38
00:06:44,570 --> 00:06:48,199
I just kept walking around the apartment, saying over and over
"They're gone, they're gone..."

39
00:06:48,242 --> 00:06:50,092
I guess I was half crazy.

40
00:06:50,653 --> 00:06:53,443
Well, that was four months ago and...

41
00:06:53,444 --> 00:06:56,233
what I've got to do now is start making demands on myself.

42
00:06:56,400 --> 00:06:58,292
Your first class is next Monday.

43
00:06:58,419 --> 00:07:00,660
I’ve set up a meeting for it tomorrow with some of the faculty

44
00:07:00,661 --> 00:07:02,020
You'll remember lot of them.

45
00:07:02,357 --> 00:07:03,947
Eleven okay for you?

46
00:07:04,158 --> 00:07:06,552
That's fine, Robert, thanks. Thanks for everything you've done.

47
00:07:06,553 --> 00:07:07,553
Ah, come on,

48
00:07:07,519 --> 00:07:10,363
everyone's very excited about you being here.

49
00:07:10,327 --> 00:07:13,877
A well-known alumnus and distinguished composer like yourself.

50
00:07:14,936 --> 00:07:15,759
Says who?

51
00:07:16,564 --> 00:07:17,600
Distinguished or not,

52
00:07:17,868 --> 00:07:18,909
we're glad you came.

53
00:07:22,074 --> 00:07:24,005
Okay, kids, keep it down.

54
00:07:24,174 --> 00:07:26,440
Go to the kitchen and get yourselves some cookies.

55
00:07:29,373 --> 00:07:31,826
By the way, how long are you planning to stay in the hotel.

56
00:07:31,827 --> 00:07:33,731
There's plenty of room for you here, you know.

57
00:07:33,794 --> 00:07:35,186
Oh no, thanks, Eva. I think...

58
00:07:35,186 --> 00:07:38,954
I’m gonna find a house... to rent. I’ve got some things coming out.

59
00:07:38,954 --> 00:07:41,946
What I need is a place I can lock myself in and pound away at the piano.

60
00:07:41,947 --> 00:07:43,132
A place I can work.

61
00:07:43,133 --> 00:07:46,949
I have a friend who works for the Historical Preservation Society.

62
00:07:46,950 --> 00:07:49,569
They have old houses that I'm sure they rent.

63
00:07:49,570 --> 00:07:52,440
- We'll see what she can come up with for you.
- Good.

64
00:08:13,085 --> 00:08:14,825
- Mr. Russell?
- Yes.

65
00:08:15,098 --> 00:08:16,569
Hello I’m Claire Norman.

66
00:08:16,923 --> 00:08:18,712
Why don't you hop in and we'll drive up.

67
00:08:19,590 --> 00:08:20,352
Fine.

68
00:08:59,313 --> 00:09:03,673
- When was the house last occupied?
- Let's see... About 12 years ago.

69
00:09:03,673 --> 00:09:07,609
It's been with the Historical Society for the past 12 years.

70
00:09:10,723 --> 00:09:11,930
There we go.

71
00:09:23,476 --> 00:09:27,252
There were plans at one time to turn it into some kind of a museum.

72
00:09:27,756 --> 00:09:30,948
But I don't know, I guess the house was meant to be lived in.

73
00:09:32,832 --> 00:09:34,272
Why hasn't it been lived in?

74
00:09:35,122 --> 00:09:37,898
Well I've only been with the Society for a year now.

75
00:09:38,075 --> 00:09:41,578
The impression I get is that they havn't tried very hard with this place.

76
00:09:42,507 --> 00:09:44,491
Of course it does need a lot of work.

77
00:09:46,378 --> 00:09:47,817
And there's some pieces here

78
00:09:48,413 --> 00:09:50,083
that are just stored.

79
00:09:51,080 --> 00:09:52,223
You'd have your pick of them.

80
00:09:52,223 --> 00:09:53,831
You know, whatever you like.

81
00:09:57,159 --> 00:09:58,339
Kitchen's in here.

82
00:09:58,489 --> 00:10:00,809
What does it take to maintain a house of this size?

83
00:10:00,935 --> 00:10:06,565
Oh, we have a man who looks after all this places: Mr. Tuttle.

84
00:10:07,692 --> 00:10:08,972
And...

85
00:10:11,106 --> 00:10:12,844
this is the music room.

86
00:10:14,110 --> 00:10:17,154
This is really why I thought of you and this house.

87
00:10:18,804 --> 00:10:23,444
The piano was left here when the society took over,
just too much trouble to move, really.

88
00:10:23,548 --> 00:10:25,892
It must be in very bad shape.

89
00:10:29,682 --> 00:10:31,267
What are the terms?

90
00:11:38,098 --> 00:11:40,026
Sorry to disturb your composing.

91
00:11:40,253 --> 00:11:41,787
That's alright, Mr Tuttle.

92
00:11:41,925 --> 00:11:43,421
This has already been composed.

93
00:11:43,463 --> 00:11:46,257
There's a man at the front... wants to deliver a water-storage tank.

94
00:11:46,282 --> 00:11:47,415
Says you called him.

95
00:11:47,416 --> 00:11:48,416
Okay.

96
00:12:11,669 --> 00:12:13,294
Manage to do any writing?

97
00:12:13,228 --> 00:12:16,332
Yes, I’m still working on the second movement. Same old problem.

98
00:12:16,868 --> 00:12:18,429
Well, maybe the lectures will help...

99
00:12:18,775 --> 00:12:20,278
Get some new ideas.

100
00:12:39,645 --> 00:12:41,191
It’s my understanding...

101
00:12:43,065 --> 00:12:44,345
that there are...

102
00:12:45,257 --> 00:12:47,545
23 students registered...

103
00:12:50,191 --> 00:12:53,534
for this series of lectures on advanced musical form.

104
00:12:54,152 --> 00:12:56,679
Now we all know that it’s not raining outside.

105
00:12:58,219 --> 00:13:02,107
And unless there's a fire in some other
part of the building we wouldn't know about,

106
00:13:03,403 --> 00:13:06,347
there's an awful lot of people here with nothing better to do.

107
00:13:07,983 --> 00:13:08,958
However,

108
00:13:10,069 --> 00:13:13,309
we'll know more after the second lecture.

109
00:13:15,381 --> 00:13:16,965
I’m sure there are many of you

110
00:13:17,887 --> 00:13:19,510
who may recognize this.

111
00:13:52,223 --> 00:13:57,623
- It sounds a little bit better with an orchestra than with a piano.
- Oh no, you made it sound fine in class.

112
00:13:57,618 --> 00:13:59,810
John's secret is that he's a natural ham.

113
00:13:59,811 --> 00:14:01,074
Ah, you're going too far.

114
00:14:02,096 --> 00:14:04,960
- lf you can't find your way back ...
- Send out a search party.

115
00:14:07,752 --> 00:14:08,497
I'm sorry.

116
00:14:14,749 --> 00:14:15,701
Hi!

117
00:14:16,749 --> 00:14:18,186
I'd like you to meet my mother.

118
00:14:18,186 --> 00:14:20,157
- How do you do, Mrs. Norman?
- How do you do?

119
00:14:20,199 --> 00:14:23,370
This is John Russell. You remember the Chessman House?

120
00:14:23,991 --> 00:14:28,071
Oh, oh yes, yes. I’m very pleased to meet you, Mr... Russel.

121
00:14:28,421 --> 00:14:30,172
How are you liking the place?

122
00:14:30,285 --> 00:14:31,126
Fine.

123
00:14:31,947 --> 00:14:33,596
It’s so... large.

124
00:14:34,258 --> 00:14:35,555
Ladies and gentlemen,

125
00:14:35,891 --> 00:14:37,890
may I have your attention please?

126
00:14:39,192 --> 00:14:42,096
I’d like to introduce Senator Joseph Carmichael

127
00:14:42,096 --> 00:14:43,231
-  and his son:
- My God!

128
00:14:43,231 --> 00:14:45,359
- congressman Eugene Carmichael.
- He's going to make another speech.

129
00:14:45,695 --> 00:14:49,856
Oh yeah, hearing this lifelong Republican commenting on a Democrat.

130
00:14:51,822 --> 00:14:54,134
You know how I hate making speeches.

131
00:14:55,311 --> 00:14:58,383
But sometimes, on a very special occasion,

132
00:14:58,383 --> 00:15:01,553
like raising money for our magnificent Symphony Orchestra...

133
00:15:01,763 --> 00:15:04,195
And weren't they fantastic tonight?

134
00:15:07,168 --> 00:15:08,146
Damn right!

135
00:15:08,616 --> 00:15:10,192
Now I’m just going to get a drink.

136
00:15:10,192 --> 00:15:11,879
I think I'll join you.

137
00:15:12,515 --> 00:15:13,995
I'll be right back, mother.

138
00:15:16,234 --> 00:15:17,202
Thank you.

139
00:15:19,902 --> 00:15:20,581
Thank you.

140
00:15:21,319 --> 00:15:23,485
Actually, he's on our Board of Directors,

141
00:15:23,485 --> 00:15:25,813
at the Historical Preservation Society.

142
00:15:25,839 --> 00:15:28,461
In fact he's become our number one philanthropist.

143
00:15:30,004 --> 00:15:31,770
So, you're getting settled in then?

144
00:15:31,668 --> 00:15:33,137
- Oh yes.
- Good.

145
00:15:33,137 --> 00:15:36,521
There's some things at the Society office that belong to your house.

146
00:15:36,706 --> 00:15:38,515
I'll see if I can dig them up for you.

147
00:15:39,348 --> 00:15:41,090
I’m glad you took the house.

148
00:18:42,228 --> 00:18:43,122
Mr. Tuttle?

149
00:18:45,084 --> 00:18:46,176
Mr. Tuttle?

150
00:18:47,772 --> 00:18:48,707
Yes, Mr. Russell.

151
00:18:50,078 --> 00:18:51,606
You frightened me.

152
00:18:52,774 --> 00:18:56,389
Is anyone else here? Mrs Riss in cleaning today?

153
00:18:56,389 --> 00:18:58,028
No, sir. Just me.

154
00:18:59,026 --> 00:18:59,734
Okay.

155
00:20:39,524 --> 00:20:40,547
That's lovely.

156
00:20:41,362 --> 00:20:42,346
The music.

157
00:20:42,472 --> 00:20:44,556
- Hello!
- Hi!

158
00:20:44,622 --> 00:20:46,862
It has the quality of a lullaby.

159
00:20:46,862 --> 00:20:49,063
Yes it is, in a certain way.

160
00:20:49,063 --> 00:20:51,038
Well, here we are, as promised.

161
00:20:51,752 --> 00:20:55,992
These are some assorted prints that used to hang in the house.

162
00:20:56,786 --> 00:20:58,199
And this...

163
00:20:59,082 --> 00:21:03,074
is an old, restored photograph taken from the back of the house.

164
00:21:04,061 --> 00:21:04,916
Beautiful.

165
00:21:07,105 --> 00:21:11,801
I tried to call you first, but information can't give your number out yet.

166
00:21:12,874 --> 00:21:15,440
That's a beautiful piece.

167
00:21:15,650 --> 00:21:17,314
Did you refinish it?

168
00:21:17,314 --> 00:21:18,665
I didn't, no.

169
00:21:23,183 --> 00:21:24,799
That was Kathy's, my daughter.

170
00:21:33,893 --> 00:21:35,773
Well I guess I’d better be off.

171
00:21:36,098 --> 00:21:37,962
I hope you like the prints.

172
00:21:38,173 --> 00:21:39,277
Thank you.

173
00:21:42,260 --> 00:21:43,571
Are you going riding?

174
00:21:44,177 --> 00:21:44,902
Yes.

175
00:21:46,030 --> 00:21:47,077
Do you ride?

176
00:22:31,047 --> 00:22:31,910
John?

177
00:22:33,288 --> 00:22:34,330
What's the matter?

178
00:22:36,543 --> 00:22:39,081
I was just thinking about my daughter Kathy.

179
00:22:41,241 --> 00:22:43,145
How much she loved horses.

180
00:23:24,910 --> 00:23:26,990
An airlock, somewhere.

181
00:23:27,224 --> 00:23:29,470
It was too loud, too rhythmic.

182
00:23:32,630 --> 00:23:34,710
Well, it's starting at least.

183
00:23:36,992 --> 00:23:39,223
Why would it happen two mornings in a row,

184
00:23:40,136 --> 00:23:41,842
precisely at 6 o'clock?

185
00:23:43,033 --> 00:23:46,601
Why does it go on for about half a minute and then stops dead.
It doesn't make sense.

186
00:23:48,528 --> 00:23:51,111
A furnace is like anything else, Mr Russell.

187
00:23:51,345 --> 00:23:52,928
It’s got habits.

188
00:23:53,898 --> 00:23:55,675
It’s an old house.

189
00:23:56,732 --> 00:23:58,349
It makes noises.

190
00:24:21,124 --> 00:24:21,974
Very good.

191
00:24:23,683 --> 00:24:25,722
We're still not together on the off-beats.

192
00:24:26,283 --> 00:24:29,084
And Don, you're retarding a little too much...

193
00:24:29,084 --> 00:24:30,883
on the last four bars.

194
00:24:31,051 --> 00:24:32,537
Otherwise it was splendid.

195
00:24:34,631 --> 00:24:35,929
Good night.

196
00:27:53,217 --> 00:27:54,768
What I'm driving at is...

197
00:27:55,025 --> 00:27:58,278
Has... anything like this happened in the house before?

198
00:27:58,278 --> 00:28:00,141
If so, to whom, when and...

199
00:28:00,771 --> 00:28:02,386
what did they do about it ?

200
00:28:03,111 --> 00:28:05,887
Since I’ve been with the Society, the house has been empty.

201
00:28:06,743 --> 00:28:07,380
John...

202
00:28:08,305 --> 00:28:10,176
You're working very hard.

203
00:28:10,176 --> 00:28:12,583
You've been through a terrible emotional strain.

204
00:28:12,583 --> 00:28:15,104
- Isn't it possible that you have...
- ...hallucinated. Is that what you're gonna say?

205
00:28:15,104 --> 00:28:15,832
Excuse me.

206
00:28:15,832 --> 00:28:16,840
Minnie ?

207
00:28:16,840 --> 00:28:20,983
Claire, there's a call for you. Your mother. Should I tell her you're busy?

208
00:28:21,058 --> 00:28:24,314
I'll be right there. Excuse me, John, just for a minute.

209
00:28:32,670 --> 00:28:35,990
You know, there's some questions about your lease, Mr. Russell.

210
00:28:36,244 --> 00:28:37,381
What do you mean?

211
00:28:38,620 --> 00:28:40,372
That house shouldn't have been rented.

212
00:28:40,692 --> 00:28:43,963
Miss Norman rushed the papers through our attorney's office.

213
00:28:44,813 --> 00:28:47,604
She did not use proper channels.

214
00:28:48,469 --> 00:28:50,189
Why should anyone object?

215
00:28:51,487 --> 00:28:53,964
That house is not fit to live in.

216
00:28:55,854 --> 00:28:57,974
No one has been able to live in it.

217
00:28:59,890 --> 00:29:02,075
It doesn't want people.

218
00:29:03,806 --> 00:29:05,683
Then there has been trouble in the house before.

219
00:36:44,263 --> 00:36:45,862
Claire, listen. It’s note for note.

220
00:36:45,862 --> 00:36:47,686
Same tempo and even the same key.

221
00:36:48,943 --> 00:36:49,972
What do you think?

222
00:36:50,858 --> 00:36:51,986
I don't know.

223
00:36:52,566 --> 00:36:54,558
It’s a startling coincidence.

224
00:36:56,440 --> 00:36:59,681
But that melody must have been very popular at one time,

225
00:36:59,681 --> 00:37:01,392
or it wouldn't be on a music box.

226
00:37:01,392 --> 00:37:03,649
I agree, but I swear I never heard it

227
00:37:04,114 --> 00:37:06,995
before I played it and recorded it that day you came over.

228
00:37:06,995 --> 00:37:08,787
No, there's something!

229
00:37:09,687 --> 00:37:10,671
Something.

230
00:37:10,671 --> 00:37:12,934
It’s happened before here. I’m not the first.

231
00:37:13,325 --> 00:37:16,269
I went all over the files very carefully.

232
00:37:16,684 --> 00:37:19,045
All the way back to 1920.

233
00:37:19,250 --> 00:37:21,356
Nothing out of the ordinary.

234
00:37:21,860 --> 00:37:23,035
Miss Huxley...

235
00:37:23,771 --> 00:37:27,140
Minnie's a highly eccentric old woman, but she'd never...

236
00:37:28,124 --> 00:37:30,757
She said the house didn't want people. She's mistaken.

237
00:37:31,040 --> 00:37:34,727
Whatever it is... it's trying desperately to communicate.

238
00:37:35,207 --> 00:37:36,855
The banging, the water taps,

239
00:37:36,855 --> 00:37:39,430
the broken window panes. All the glass fell outward.

240
00:37:39,430 --> 00:37:40,943
It has to be done from the inside.

241
00:37:40,833 --> 00:37:42,070
Everything that's happened

242
00:37:42,857 --> 00:37:44,857
has been designed to get me into that attic room.

243
00:37:46,957 --> 00:37:48,294
I want to see it.

244
00:38:06,180 --> 00:38:07,988
Look at that book on the desk.

245
00:38:16,457 --> 00:38:18,232
C.S.B.

246
00:38:18,442 --> 00:38:20,264
January 4th

247
00:38:20,474 --> 00:38:22,200
1909.

248
00:38:23,966 --> 00:38:25,989
It’s a little child's writing.

249
00:38:27,364 --> 00:38:29,540
1909. Who could have lived here then?

250
00:38:33,364 --> 00:38:36,004
This is where I found the music box on the mantel.

251
00:38:42,257 --> 00:38:43,416
Look at this wheelchair.

252
00:38:45,823 --> 00:38:47,242
My God!

253
00:38:49,354 --> 00:38:51,041
It’s so small.

254
00:38:54,506 --> 00:38:56,086
What was this room?

255
00:39:31,883 --> 00:39:35,491
Former residents, William Saracino and family, architect.

256
00:39:36,162 --> 00:39:39,370
Bought the place in 1965, sold it in 1967.

257
00:39:39,980 --> 00:39:43,876
Purchased for the Society of Historical Preservation, November 1967,

258
00:39:43,876 --> 00:39:46,306
through a generous grant from the Carmichael Foundation.

259
00:39:46,306 --> 00:39:47,714
- That's the senator?
- Yes.

260
00:39:48,540 --> 00:39:49,666
Great philantropist.

261
00:39:49,566 --> 00:39:51,877
Now where is the rest of this file?

262
00:39:51,877 --> 00:39:53,438
No previous occupants...

263
